{{also|ἄνθρωπος}}
==Greek==

===Etymology===
Inherited<ref>{{R:DSMG}}</ref> from {{inh|el|grc|ἄνθρωπος||man}}, as also are variants<ref>[http://repository.academyofathens.gr/kendi/index.php/gr/listItems/118776 άνθρωπος] - ''Historical Dictionary of the Academy of Athens'', vol.2</ref> like {{m|el|άθρωπος}}, already since {{m|grc|ἄθρωπος}} of the 3rd century.<ref>[https://www.greek-language.gr/greekLang/medieval_greek/em_kriaras/scanned_new/index.html?start=301&id=50&show=1 p.214], [https://www.greek-language.gr/greekLang/medieval_greek/em_kriaras/scanned_new/index.html?start=301&id=50&show=1 215] - {{R:Kriaras Medieval2}}</ref><ref>{{R:Kriaras Medieval}}</ref><br>
According to other etymologists, an internal learned borrowing,<ref>{{R:Georgakas}}</ref> replacing {{m|el|άθρωπος}}.<ref>{{cite-book|author=Julián Mendez Dosuna|chapter=Once again on allophonic spellings in Ancient Greek|title=Miscellanea Indogermanica: Festschrift for José Luis García Ramón herausgegeben von 65. Geburtstag|editors=Ivo Hajnal, Daniel Kölligan, Katharina Zipser|page=491|location=Innsbruck|year=2017|publisher=Innsbrucker Beiträge zur Sprachwissenschaft}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|el|/ˈan.θɾo.pos/}}
* {{audio|el|El-άνθρωπος.ogg}}
* {{hyphenation|el|άν|θρω|πος}}

===Noun===
{{el-noun|m|άνθρωποι}}

# a [[human]]; [[person]]; the species [[man]]
## {{lb|el|in the plural}} [[people]]

====Usage notes====
This masculine noun covers both male and female meanings of the definition. Articles and adjectives will both follow the masculine gender.

